Fussing layers with chloroform works for pla
Also a pair of proper gloves as chloroform seems to melt the latex.
Edit: some people has raised concerns about leftovers or carbon based compounds remaining on the surface. Though it leaves a smooth surface, health might outweigh the benefits.

postsData.text: Has anyone been able to configure some type of mask for people with a tracheostomy? They don’t breathe through their nose and because of that all germs go directly into the lungs. A lot of kids do not tolerate HMEs or Passy-Muir valves, anything that actually attached to a trach itself. A bib/bandana unfortunately doesn’t filter the air. For many, going to appointments right now is still essential and cannot be done over the phone.

postsData.text: I have an issue that I’m hoping some of you guys can help me with. I have a narrow nose and wear glasses, and every time I put on a dust mask my glasses immediately fog up when I breathe. The little metal strips over the bridge of the nose is entirely useless since it doesn’t have enough strength to mold the mask to the contours of my nose, and I’ve tried all sorts of different ways to position the mask and my glasses to no avail. Do any of you guys have suggestions for how I can fix this with common household items? I don’t have a 3D printer or anything fancy unfortunately 😢

Looking for insight & suggestions on headbands with buttons using what resources I have. I’ve read through the other threads posted here which were super helpful but looking for a bit more.
A factory I’ve worked with in the past graciously donated 1000 fabric headbands to me and I was able to acquire buttons locally. Since there are different types of masks, I’m exploring different placements of buttons for different needs (i.e. mask straps that are too big, ear pain, N95 straps vs. looped straps, etc). Any suggestions as to how to make these in the most helpful way would be much appreciated.

postsData.text:
In San Diego I'm trying a slightly different approach with 3D printed molds, silicone rubber (grey) and urethane resin (black) to make a mask that can be sanitized and reused. The rubber part against the face, gives a tight but comfortable seal.
The mask can be used with a variety of filter materials. Nylon cord with a slip know at the back of the neck is used to hold it in place. As you may have noticed, elastic cord is hard to find.
The molds take longer to design and make, but once you have them, parts can be casted faster then printing a similar design.
The next step is to get a few people to try it and see how it fits.
